<subSubSection pageId="41" pageNumber="74" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="41" pageNumber="74">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="41" pageNumber="74">
The genus 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Elmidae" genus="Pharceonus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pharceonus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pharceonus</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from all other genera of Laraine 
<taxonomicName family="Elmidae" lsidName="" pageId="41" pageNumber="74" rank="family">Elmidae</taxonomicName>
that occur in South America by its small size and distinctive pronotum. All 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Elmidae" genus="Pharceonus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pharceonus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pharceonus</taxonomicName>
species are small (3.1-4.3 mm), but generally larger than the similar genus 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Elmidae" genus="Phanocerus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phanocerus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Phanocerus</taxonomicName>
, in various shades of medium to dark brown, with a pronotum that has a distinctive transverse bisinuate impression at the apical third and a transverse, bisinuate impression subbasally (Fig. 83). These two impressions form two gibbosities on the basal two thirds of the pronotum (Fig. 83).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="41" pageNumber="74">
Distribution. 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Elmidae" genus="Pharceonus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pharceonus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pharceonus</taxonomicName>
species occur throughout southern Central America and northern South America, from Costa Rica south to Peru (pers. obs.).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="41" pageNumber="74">
Habitat. Members of this genus can be found on roots and woody debris in small to medium forested streams and seeps, as well as in the benthos, among gravel and sometimes on on rocky substrate (
<bibRefCitation author="Spangler, PJ" journalOrPublisher="Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology" pageId="56" pageNumber="89" title="The Aquatic Beetle Subfamily Larainae (Coleoptera: Elmidae) in Mexico, Central America, and the West Indies." volume="528" year="1992">Spangler and Santiago-Fragoso 1992</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
